"When the United States gives us security guarantees > we will be ready to sit down and we will enter diplomacy," the Ukrainian president explained. The U.S. "want this agreement (on the exploitation of minerals, ndr) and we are not against the agreement, but we want to understand what guarantees this agreement will bring us and what will be the next steps".
Zelensky responded with a "yes, of course" to the journalist's question that asked him if he believed that the relationship with Trump could still be saved, stressing that he did not want to lose the United States as a partner, while stating that he wants Trump to be "more on our side". "That's why - he added - I always thank your people on behalf of my people. Thanks to the President and Congress, but first of all to your people." &nbsp;
Zelensky admitted that it would be "difficult" for Ukraine to resist the invasion of Russian forces without American support. "It'll be hard for us," "That's why I'm here. That is why we are discussing future negotiations. It will be difficult without your support," the Ukrainian leader said. Zelensky then responded "I don't know" to the journalist asking him if he thought Trump and J. D. Vance's attack on him had been prepared.
It started with a handshake, with compliments on Zelensky's elegance. And it ended with an unprecedented clash in the history of diplomacy, the conversation at the White House between American President Donald Trump and Ukrainian leader. Twenty minutes of barrel and response without filters, in front of the cameras around the world. And that very hard accusation of Trump in Zelensky: "You're playing with the Third World War">.
