AGI - The appeal launched yesterday by Kurdish leader Abdullah Ocalan, who asked to lay the weapons to the separatist organization Pkk founded by him, could represent a historical turning point and the end of a 40-year conflict and cost the life to about 50 thousand people.
&nbsp;
The appeal of the Kurdish leader in fact puts both the Pkk and the entire region before a crossroads: peace or years of war. After spending 26 years in a maximum security prison, the question is whether Ocalan has retained the authority to decrete the group's dissolution and whether it will follow or choose the war with Turkey. A war that Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan has no intention of losing, especially before a country that continues to promise "a Turkey without terror".
<div </div
On the one hand there is the authority of Ocalan, on the other also the situation of the Pkk, changed a lot in recent years. The organization has been reduced to the minimum terms. In Turkey the last attack, isolated, dates back to November 2022, but the operations of the group in the south east by Kurdish majority of the country were almost eliminated after the violent operations carried out by Erdogan in 2016. Similarly, the perception of the Pkk has changed to most of the Kurdish population which is no longer recognized in the guerrilla. The choice of Erdogan to fight this war only with the special forces allowed him to achieve results and stem the Pkk until he pushed him off the border. The sanctuaries of the group are on the indomitable mountains of Iraqi Kurdistan. A harsh territory, where Ankara's army continued to attack seamlessly, but without failing.
&nbsp;
The Pkk is in the extreme, continuous targets of the Turkish drones, but the conflict goes on. If Ocalan's appeal falls into the void Turkish operations are destined to intensify in the entire area and the Pkk could hardly counteract. Erdogan also has the full support of the other Kurdish leader, Barzani, whose family governs Iraqi Kurdistan and has always considered the Pkk an enemy. In recent months, the Baghdad government has also supported Ankara against the Pkk with a collaboration protocol.
&nbsp;
A different and perhaps even more uncertain situation concerns the Kurdish separatists of Ypg in the north east of Syria. The Akp party of Erdogan today specified that the Ocalan appeal must also concern Ypg. A rib of the Pkk, born under a different acronym not to end in the list of terrorist organizations, but that with Ocalan in prison and with the support of the U.S. has taken a different road. Ypg has gained recognition in the years of the struggle at Isis, manages the provinces of the north-east Syrian, controls some cities, the detention camps of the Isis families and the captivity of the caliphate.
&nbsp;
The Kurdish leader asked to depose the weapons to "all armed groups", but at the moment the reaction from the north east of Syria was cold. In the past years the Turkish army has carried out two different operations and subtracted territory to Ypg. Incursions lasted a few days that saw the Turks advance without major problems. The north of Syria, unlike the harsh mountains of northern Iraq, is in fact hilly and barren, unfit by hand by the guerrillas.
&nbsp;
The U.S. has curbed Ankara's advance, but President Donald Trump does not seem likely to guarantee Ypg the support of his predecessors. It is no coincidence that the two Turkish military operations against Ypg were launched in 2018 and 2019, both during Trump's first term. With the fall of the Damascus regime Ankara has become a central actor in Syria; Kurdish separatists ended up under attack by Syrian militias supported by Turkey (Syrian Free Army, ELS) and were marginalized politically. The president of the Transitional Government Ahmed Al Sharaa, asked for the return of the territories of the north east and offered Ypg to enter the Syrian army.
&nbsp;
Also in this case the reaction was cold and Ypg was excluded from the table of the Syrian constituent ending isolated. If in Syria the Ocalan appeal should end up unheard, it is very likely that Ypg is in the crossfire of the Turkish troops, of the Syrian militiamen of ELS, but also of the new army of Damascus that is born precisely with the collaboration of Ankara. Erdogan does not want Ypg on its own borders, Al Sharaa does not seem willing to contradict him and for Ypg there may not be escape.&nbsp;
